snippet.textDisplay: Timelords always recognize each other; even with new regenerations.  But not here.  I had the same problem with Capaldi not recognizing Missy as The Master.  I could explain that one away with Missy because The Master is a body thief when he runs out of regenerations.  (And Simm had, like, REALLY killed himself a few times; so maybe he was out of them again.)  So Missy could have been a stolen body.  But this time O's body is in The Master's pocket.  While it's neat to see the Tissue Compressor again, that means he can't be wearing O's stolen body.  So why didn't The Doctor recognize him?  (Answer.... Chibnal hasn't done a lot of research, I know.  But that's not a satisfying answer.)

Not for joy, but for the sadness that this new era (Chibnall) has chosen to forget Missy.
Throughout years of watching, I always wanted and believe the Master will be back. But after seeing Missy's exit. I felt it was the perfect ending for the Master.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm still waiting for Chibnall to write an episode that causes us to care at all about the companions this regeneration. Every other regeneration we have been given an insight into the companion's lives which make us care about them. The only companion this time that I give any care for is the grandfather, Graham. Yaz could be killed off, and Ryan too, and I wouldn't care one bit. So far, all they are is someone for the storyline to drag along. We have a police officer who doesn't appear to know anything about being a police officer, and a whining guy who hasn't been much of anything at all.
If they dropped the dead weight, maybe there might be some kind of a good story line.
I think that Chibnall is too much of a fan boy, and believes that all of us too stupid to put together a multifaceted, but connected, storyline. I think that he thinks that we need Michael Bay type episodes, with explosions and gratuitous action, so he can skip the meat, and go straight to the pudding.
I, personally would have liked to have waited until the 3rd or 4th episode before we found out about the master. Let us believe that O was a good guy, and Barton was the real bad guy. That way we would have let our guard down and the surprise reveal would have been so much better. O should have been brought along on a few encounters, and been shown to be apparently helpful, all the while gathering more ways to get his revenge on the Doctor.
I hope we don't get another season of massive plot holes, half hearted storytelling, and pathetic SJW garbage thrown at us, like he did last season.

snippet.textDisplay: "What?!....Call you MASTER?" Oh, this episode now makes want Season 12 even more in my digital collection. This season now feels more like WHO than last Season 11 "experiment". I wish there were more context about the Doctor being female. The writers could have fun with the ideas and make Jodie's Doctor memorable at the same time! Example, "I forgot I cannot leave THE SEAT up anymore." This is new territory...explore it...embrace it...love it...oh, and that new MASTER...I did not see that coming....hehe. 😁😃🙂😳
